      "source_region": "div.problem-additional-text",
      "text": "[Gu04] Guy, Richard K., Unsolved problems in number theory. (2004), xviii+437."
    },
    "remarks": {
      "sha256": "a44eb3b6aaef6df65273fd3e181d8ba5ca2bb36da26ff2535d2e4f55987b90a6",
      "source_region": "div.problem-additional-text",
      "text": "This is discussed in problem B11 of Guy's collection \\cite{Gu04}."
    },
    "statement": {
      "sha256": "f0920e5ffe34b44a547f7da8e52147078959c3286729dc4d2ae15dcb41466c3f",
      "source_region": "div#content",
      "text": "Let $f(n)$ count the number of solutions to $k\\sigma(k)=n$, where $\\sigma(k)$ is the sum of divisors of $k$. Is it true that $f(n)\\leq n^{o(\\frac{1}{\\log\\log n})}$? Perhaps even $\\leq (\\log n)^{O(1)}$?"
    }
  },
